Reports columns in the USING clause that does not exist in both tables.
<p>Example (MySQL):</p>
<pre><code>CREATE TABLE t1 (i INT, j INT);
CREATE TABLE t2 (k INT, l INT);
SELECT * FROM t1 JOIN t2 USING (j);</code></pre>
<p>In USING clauses, a column name must be present in both tables, and the SELECT query will automatically join
  those tables by using the given column name. As we do not have the <code>j</code> column in <code>t2</code>, we can
  rewrite the query using ON. The ON clause can join tables where the column names do not match in both tables.</p>
<pre><code>SELECT * FROM t1 JOIN t2 ON t1.j = t2.l;</code></pre>
